  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN142.2-kilavi">iravukkuṟi vantu nīṅkun talaimakaṉ taṉ neñciṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">What HE who left having come from the night tryst said to his heart.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="AN142.2">
              <l>ilamala raṉṉa vañcen nāviṟ</l>
            <l>pulamīk kūṟum puraiyō rēttap</l>
            <l>palarmēn tōṉṟiya kavikai vaḷḷal</l>
            <l>ciṟaiyarun tāṉai velpōr māntaram</l>
            <l>poṟaiyaṉ kaṭuṅkōp pāṭic ceṉṟa</l>
            <l>kuṟaiyōr koḷkalam pōla naṉṟu</l>
            <l>muvaviṉi vāḻiye ṉeñcē kātali</l>
            <l>muṟaiyiyal <supplied>va</supplied>ḻāa tāṟṟip peṟṟa</l>
            <l>kaṟaiyaṭi yāṉai naṉṉaṉ pāḻi</l>
            <l>yūṭṭaru marapi ṉañcuvaru pēeyk</l>
            <l>kūṭṭetir koṇṭa vāymoḻi miñili</l>
            <l>puḷḷiṟ kēma mākiya perumpeyar</l>
            <l>veḷḷat tāṉai yatikaṟ koṉṟuvan</l>
            <l>toḷvā ḷamalai yāṭiya ñāṭpiṟ</l>
            <l>palaraṟi vuṟuta lañcip paipaya</l>
            <l>nīrttiraḷ kaṭukku mācil veḷḷi</l>
            <l>cūrppuṟu kōlvaḷai ceṟitta muṉkaik</l>
            <l>kuṟai<supplied>ya</supplied>ṟa laṉṉa virumpal kūnta</l>
            <l>liṭaṉil ciṟupuṟat tiḻaiyoṭu tuyalvarak</l>
            <l>kaṭaṉmīṉ ṟuñcu naḷḷeṉ yāmat</l>
            <l>turuvukiḷa rōviṉaip polinta pāvai</l>
            <l>yiyalkaṟ ṟaṉṉa votukkiṉaḷ vantu</l>
            <l>peyalaik kalaṅkiya malaippūṅ kōtai</l>
            <l>viyaleṟi poṉṉiṟ koṅkucōr puṟaippat</l>
            <l>toṭikkaṇ vaṭuppaṭa muyaṅkiṉaḷ</l>
            <l>vaṭippuṟu narampiṟ ṟivviya moḻintē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>Like the ornaments taken by supplicants (6a-c)</l>
                <l>who had gone singing to Māntaram Poṟaiyaṉ (5)</l>
                <l>Kaṭumkō, of victorious battles, with an army difficult to restrain, (4)</l>
                <l>a donor with eager hands celebrated by many people, (3)</l>
                <l>so that great people esteemed for [their] erudition praise [him]</l>
                <l>with pretty tongues red like silk-cotton blossoms, (1f.)</l>
                <l>well rejoice now, oh my heart. [Our] love, (6d-7)</l>
                <l>afraid that many will have knowledge, (15a-c)</l>
                <l>like in the battle, where, (14d)</l>
                <l>in the Pāḻi of Naṉṉaṉ with mortar-legged elephants</l>
                <l>that were ably obtained by not swerving from the natural order, (8f.)</l>
                <l>Miñili of true words, who received the assistance</l>
                <l>of the fearful demonesses by custom difficult to feed (10f.)</l>
                <l>rejoiced in killing Atikaṉ, with flood of an army</l>
                <l>of great repute that was a refuge to birds, (12f.)</l>
                <l>[and] danced a victory dance of bright swords, (14a-c)</l>
                <l>while [her] forearms, enclosed by gently revolving beautiful bangles</l>
                <l>of flawless silver, resembling beads of water, (15d-17)</l>
                <l>[and her] many dark tresses, like black sand from a river island,</l>
                <l>along with the jewels in the small of [her] back on the left side came into swinging, (18f.)</l>
                <l>at deepest midnight when the fish sleep in the sea, (20)</l>
                <l>she came with steps as if a wonderful vibrant figure</l>
                <l>had learned to move out of a picture shining with beauty, (21f.)</l>
                <l>[and] embraced [me] so that marks were left by the joints of [her] bangles (25)</l>
                <l>while [her] garland of flowers from the mountain stirred up by raining</l>
                <l>dripped, pollen spilling like widely glittering gold, (23f.)</l>
                <l>talking heavenly like well-tuned strings. (26)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
